reviewText: I stumbled across Jackie Warner about a year ago, when I was given a copy of herPersonal Training with Jackie: Power Circuit Training, which I love. The pace there is fast and somehow fun, without being painful (aside from the final ab circuits). In contrast, Jackie's latest offering is a whole lotta 'Ow!' packed into an itty bitty workout, capping itself at just over 30 minutes.The workout is pretty straightforward in terms of its arrangement, and includes a warmup and cooldown. There are four circuits lasting five excruciating minutes each, which focus on four general areas of the body - Glutes & Shoulders, Quads & Arms, Major Muscle Groups (hip/chest/back), and 'Core & More'. There are five compound moves, each of which last a minute, although compared to her last DVD they feel like they last eons. The compound movements either involve holding a static pose - like a pile squat or a deep runner's stretch - while moving your arms, or focusing more on moving your lower body through squats, lunges, and kicks with less range on the upper body.To put things in perspective as to how difficult this workout is, the beginner model in the video does not use weights the entire time. I strongly recommend going through your first run of the DVD weight free to get a sense of how physically challenging it is for your personal fitness level, instead of throwing in the towel halfway through when you get too tired with weights in hand. From there, sincerely, I would recommend no more than 3 lb weights given the constant level of movement and intensity of the workout. One thing I disliked about this DVD was that instead of doing five unique moves per circuit, if something needed to be done on both sides of your body, they both took up a full minute of the workout. I would have preferred to get some more variety and either switch sides halfway through a minute, or alternatively, had shorter segments and repeated a the circuit to give my body a break from holding certain positions for up to two full minutes.On the flip side, I definitely respect how hardcore this workout is for the very brief amount of time you have to commit to it. I have no doubt this DVD is as effective if not moreso than Jackie's other longer workouts, and similar programs offered by other top 'DVD trainers' out there. Jackie has a number of unique moves I've never done before, and the compound movements she has you do definitely rev up your heart rate to extreme cardio calorie burning levels while also toning your whole body. I found her instruction was a lot more focused and clear this time around as she took breaks from doing the workout herself and followed up on the form of both girls she has participating with her. I also enjoyed the fact the DVD was shot in hi-def and has a big, spacious set to make you feel a little less claustrophobic on your seventieth squat. Also kudos for finally getting chapter selection on your DVD Jackie!The four star rating for me comes from the fact that this really is just one workout, when most workout DVDs offer you two or more workouts, or at least a workout double the length that you can chop into bitty pieces if you can't do the whole thing at once. Although it is very effective at getting your heart rate going and making your muscles ache in all sorts of (fun) new ways, I would have liked to see more than one workout for the price. I also would have liked to see more variation in the moves as I said - not only for my physical desires, but also mentally - it gets pretty numbing and panicky up there when you realize you have to do the same body-burning move for another sixty agonizing seconds sometimes. Still, another good entry from Jackie that definitely has me afraid and excited for her Xtreme abs workout!
summary: Jackie's Not Kidding About the XTREME

reviewText: What I like better about this vs. Jackie's Power Circuit Training is that the moves are compound and they get your cardio going more. Because it is pretty shoulder heavy, I mostly used my lighter 5lb weights for this one, whereas for PCT I was using 10 for most stuff, because there are a lot more isolating exercises for other muscle groups.This workout is more like what you'll see with Jillian Michaels because of the compound moves and more cardio. It is slightly less intense, cardio-wise than Jillian, but what I like about this and PCT is that Jackie gives you more time with each exercise so that you are fatiguing that muscle group, whereas with Jillian you are switching way more, getting more tired with the cardio, but you don't feel like you're doing as much of a weight training workout. Because of this, I get more sore (in a good way) with Jackie than with Jillian. In this workout, I like the fact that there is no repetition of circuits or exercises, you just move from one thing to the next so you aren't getting bored with the exercises. I found myself wishing this one was ten minutes longer, though.I plan to keep trying Jackie's other videos. I like her as an instructor... she gives lots of feedback on form and she is not annoying but just encourages you.

reviewText: I work out daily but am not one to do a lot of free weight exercises.  I've been trying to do a little more lately and tried this one because I have tried several of her other dvds and have really liked them.  I may be a tad less enthusiastic about this one just because you have to do a minute of each exercise which in theory didn't sound too bad, but after seemingly endless squats, lunges and arm exercises you start to think one minute is a really long time.  As I walked up the four flights of stairs at work my quads, hamstring and glute muscles were letting me know I had got a good workout the day before in my little 32 minutes of workout.The thing I love about her workouts is that she has excellent form and shows an advanced exerciser and e one showing modifications which allows you to pick what is right for you.  You can also make the workout harder with heavier weights or easier with lighter weights or no weights at all.  I am not used to heavy weights, so I tend to stay in the 3-5# range.  For this one I did 3# for the first time and I felt that my muscles were tired.  Go lower until you know you can complete the reps and feel they were challenging enough but not so hard that you are compromising good form to make the reps.  Remember, a minute will seem like a while when you are doing squats and arm exercises at the same time.  There are a lot of big muscles working there.Overall, a nice workout if you are short on time.  If you own or have tried other Jackie Warner dvds you will get the same level of workout and instruction that you have come to expect from this top-notch teacher.
summary: she sure does pack a lot into 30 minutes!

reviewText: The first time I did this, I found it so boring and monotonous that I did not pick it up for another year.  Jackie has you do each exercise for an entire minute and I found myself thinking that this will never end.  I decided to pick it again a month ago; three times a week for two weeks.  The good news is, I believe it is effective.  It was challenging and got me to sweat.  For those who claim it doesn't, you should up your weights until it becomes a challenge.  I actually used three sets of weights - depending on the difficulty of the move for me.  The bad news is, my knees hurt after two weeks.  I am not going to rate this a "one star" or "two star" because of my particular case. I don't see any other reviewer complaining about their knees.  Just for background, I have worked out with weights for over 30 years, so I did not up and decide to workout one day from being a couch potato.  I went back to Jillian Michaels (Ripped in 30 and 30 Day Shred) the last couple of weeks, 3X a week,  and my knees have recovered.  I have also done 90 Day Supreme for the last couple of years and my knees never hurt.  (BTW, 90 Day Supreme is awesome).My main beef with this workout is the boring factor.  I find the way Jillian Michaels structures her 30 minute programs to be fast and interesting.  Before you know it, the workout is done.  Somehow, the way Jackie structured this video makes it seem endless.  I may still end up using it once in a while, because as I said before, I believe it is effective.  I may still try out another one of her videos.  Any suggestions?

reviewText: This is a 30 minute circuit training workout with a total running time of just over 30 minutes.  This does touch every major muscle group (although not as completely as Power Circuit Training which is just over 40 minutes long).  The idea behind this workout is that every exercise works multiple large and small muscle groups so that the cardio intensity is high for better fat burning and because your working multiple muscle groups, the workout is more efficient.The basic format is each exercise is about 1 minute in length and each major muscle area is worked for 4 to 5 minutes.  There are modifications given for each level (beginner through advanced) although true beginners will have a tough time making it through the entire workout.  The intensity of this workout is geared towards intermediate to advanced exercisers (it is similar in intensity to Jillian Michaels 30 day shred).For those people with knee issues, there are squats, front lunges, and reverse lunges.  There is not a lot of jumping.  There is a little bit of balance work.  The only equipment required is hand weights (3/5/8).  As with previous workouts, attention is given to proper form.  Her instructions are clear and easy to follow.  This workout does not have an ab series but abs and core are worked throughout the workout.This is a great option for people who need a tough workout but who are short on time.  This will deliver a pretty good butt kicker of a workout in 30 minutes.  Basically, this one actually lives up to the promise on the label.
summary: Excellent total body workout when time is short

reviewText: I have read a couple of opinions on fitness forums about this DVD, and they were not good.  I was so close to skipping this based on those opinions, but....I caved, and I was surprised at the intensity!!  It is only 32 minutes, however, during that time, Jackie makes you WORK.Good form is crucial to the effectiveness of this workout. Each exercise works multiple muscle groups, so for the short amount of time, Jackie gets a lot done.  Definately a timesaver =) Each exercise is done for one minute, then you move quickly to the next.Here's a breakdown of the Multi-Joint Circuits:Warm up1. Glutes & ShouldersPlie Squat with Shoulder CirclesRunner Pose with Rear Delt Raise (1 minute each leg)Curtsey Squat to Side Kick & Punch (1 minute each leg) BALANCE CHALLENGE!!Squat Pullover (use one weight)2. Quads & ArmsSquat with Bicep Curls - Concetration CurlsAlternating Front Lunges with Tricep Headbangers (use one weight)Alternating Forward Lunges with Chest FlyReverse Lunges to Front Kick & Punch (one minute each leg)3. Hip, Chest, BackWide Squat Stance (with arms alternating) Punch down & Row upOn Ground - Glute Bridge with Chest FlyCrawl out, Push up, Crawl back in, Pick up weights & do a Military PressOn Hands & Knees - Elbow to Knee, opposite arm to opposite knee4. Multi Joint Functional RoutineSplit Squat Wood Chop (one minute each leg)Holding Arms Parallel to floor, palms up - Lift Knee up while squeezing biceps to ears. On opposie leg, traditional bicep curls with elbows pinned to bodyOn Ground - Kneeling, Leaning Side (lateral) Raise (one minute each side) this really hits obliques too!Cooldown - This is a really quick Cooldown. You may want to do some additional stretching.This workout kicked my toosh!  I didn't pause it even though my body was begging me at times. One minute sometimes felt like FOREVER. This is a workout for all fitness levels - there's a modifier for beginner, she doesn't use any weights. If the workout gets too easy, up the weights. It's a solid high intermediate workout when done with weights.I appreciate that this workout is right around 30 minutes. One more 30 minute workout would have been nice....this is the reason I gave it 4 stars. Ten bucks for one workout is not much bang for my buck ; ) If you have any questions, please leave a comment and I will do my best to answer it!Efficient & effective workout =)

reviewText: I'm a runner (marathons and farther) and weights/strength training is a secondary (but necessary) pursuit for me.  I don't have time to spend more than 40-45 minutes and like to get in a full body workout in one shot.  This one fits the bill for me 100%!  It's full body, but more leg and shoulder intensive with less focus on abs (although some of the functional movements definitely work the core too!).  I generally use 8-10 lb weights, but I had to drop down to 5lbs or nothing for this workout. I really like Jackie's style --- she's tough and no nonsense, but encouraging.  (I also own and love herPersonal Training with Jackie: Power Circuit Trainingdvd.)  Due to my running, I don't look for or need cardio in my strength workouts. But this one definitely gets the heart pumping.  Added bonus if you're looking for a little cardio too.  Looking forward to progressing with this workout!

reviewText: I wanted to try out one of Jackie's workouts after hearing positive reviews. I was surprised at how much she was able to fit in in 30 minutes and impressed by her approach to the workout and tips throughout. The moves are strength training focused but really do get your heart rate up in the cardio zone. She uses hand weights throughout and incorporates movement into each exercise to work multiple muscle groups simultaneously and keep your heart rate up. There are two women exercising with her and one does modifications throughout and never uses hand weights. I consider myself an advanced beginner exerciser and I'll admit that I had to stop using the hand weights at a certain point, but I still felt the challenge when I lost them... these exercises are tough!Each exercise is done for one minute and sometimes that one minute feels like it lasts forever. In general, Jackie starts out demonstrating the exercise with everyone, then goes around to the 2 women and comments on how to correctly do the advanced and modified versions, then she joins in participating in the exercise again. I found this to be very helpful; for each exercise you're guaranteed to get an explanation of both ways to execute the movement and what to focus on. The sections are as follows: Warm up, Glutes/Shoulders, Quads/Arms, Hip/Chest/Back, Multi Joint Functional Routine, and Cooldown. The only area I felt was missing was ab work... there's some use of the core in the Multi Joint Functional Routine but not enough in my opinion. I know it's a shorter workout, but this is a main area to target in workouts and could have been focused on more in my opinion. Jackie's instructions and tips were clear and helpful and I found her personality and approach similar to Jillian Michaels but a bit less "bootcamp" in style and somewhat more approachable and friendly. If you like Jillian Michaels, you will probably like Jackie Warner.I became slightly annoyed by one of the "backup" women who would say "You're coming to me?" every time Jackie approached her to comment on her form, but this was only a slight irritation. The workout is solid and good for days where you don't want to commit an hour of your time but still want a tough workout.

reviewText: I'm a fan of Jackie's show, had no idea she had her own DVD's - got this one because I could really use a time saving workout that kicks my butt and the other reviews are so high - this did not disappoint - it's SOOOO good! Jackie is fun, engaging, supportive, assertive - her helpers are fantastic - it's just perfect.You can tell that she really knows what to do and say to motivate people to keep going - her personality is right on point - she keeps you going, reminds you to breathe, offers encouragement, but this isn't a cuddle fest - she's here to WORK you, and this thing is INSANE!I couldn't even get through it the first time, I think I made it through 20 minutes - it really is a total body workout with cardio - you get pumping and sweating w/in seconds of starting it. Her 2 assistants are great as well - she let's you know right in the beginning that one will be doing the more challenging moves, and the other will be doing the modifications to make it a little easier on us nubes.Love, love, love this - going to get all of her work out's now!
